footer: footer.title: {[Helvetica x 9]}{[8.0 x 5, 5.656 x 4]}{[normal x 9]}{[null x 8, italic]} //_{aNote: Boldface indicates statistical signifciance (p< 0.05).} Data were included for children aged 9–17 years from households earning ≆ 185% of the Federal Poverty Level who participated in the National _{b Health and Nutrition Examination Survey between 2003 and 2012.} _{c All values excluding “p, trend”are given as mean difference from the reference category and 95% CIs (in parentheses).} Models were adjusted for age, race/ethnicity, number of weekly school lunches reported consumed by child, and household size. When SNAP was modeled as the primary exposure, a continuous term for NSLP participation (lunches/week) was also included in the model. When NSLP participation _{d was modeled as the primary exposure, a binary variable for SNAP participation (yes/no) was also included in the model.} p for trend corresponds to the Wald test p-value when “household food security”was modeled as a continuous term. NSLP, National School Lunch Program; SNAP, Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program.
